### 1. The "Starvation" Deadlock
Your Core was spawning bots anytime it had enough Titanium for a Builder Bot (`10 * scale`). However, a bot needs `80 Ti` to build a Harvester and `~30 Ti` to lay a conveyor line. Because the Core instantly spent all incoming Ti on *new* bots, the exploring bots never had enough to build a Harvester! They would wait, their `stuck_counter` would hit 5, and they would blindly suicide. 
**Fix:** The Core must calculate an "Expedition Cost" (`~150 * scale`) and only spawn a bot when it has enough Ti to fund the entire mining operation from start to finish.

### 2. Pathfinding Loop-Time Exhaustion
A* pathfinding was recalculated on *every single tick* for returning bots. This ate into the 2ms limit, causing engine dropouts, and made routing unpredictable.
**Fix:** Calculate the path *once* when the ore is found, store it as an array, and simply step along it.

### 3. Role Rigidity & Conveyor Webbing
Bots were randomly guessing roles. The winning bot creates dedicated, parallel mining lines that stream resources backward and then self-destructs the builder to reduce scale penalties.
**Fix:** We've introduced a State Machine (`SCOUT` -> `GOTO_ORE` -> `PLAN_LINE` -> `BUILD_LINE`). When a bot finishes pulling its conveyor line back to the Core (or Foundry), it `self_destruct()`s, returning its 10% scaling cost to the pool so future buildings remain cheap!

